Cylindropuntia prolifera is a type of cactus native to the deserts of southwestern United States and northern Mexico. 
It is commonly known as the Coastal cholla or the Jumping cholla. 
The plant has a greenish-gray tangled stem with cylindrical segments that are covered in rigid, yellowish spines. 
Its spines are barbed, which allows them to easily detach and attach to clothing or skin of animals or people, giving the impression that they have "jumped". 
The fruits of Cylindropuntia prolifera are reddish-brown and are covered in papery sheaths. 
This cactus is often found in desert habitats, along sandy washes, and on rocky slopes. 
Cylindropuntia prolifera is highly adaptable to different environments and is thus used for erosion control, as well as ornamental landscaping.
